Note:
==============================================================================
Color Temperature - Kelvin to Chromaticity / RGB Conversion
==============================================================================

This module implements the daylight-locus / Planckian-locus
approximations that map an absolute temperature in Kelvin to a CIE
xy chromaticity and an sRGB linear-RGB tristimulus.

Two locus formulas are supported:

  Planckian locus (CIE Publication 15:2004, Section 9.1):
      A blackbody radiator at temperature T (1000-25000 K) emits light
      whose CIE 1931 chromaticity follows a smooth curve in the xy plane.
      We use the Krystek 1985 cubic-Hermite approximation
          (M. Krystek, "An algorithm to calculate correlated colour
           temperature", Color Research & Application 10(1), pp. 38-40,
           1985)
      which matches the published Planckian locus to <0.0003 chromaticity
      error across the supported range.

  Daylight locus (CIE Publication 15:2004, Section 6.4.4.1):
      The CIE D-illuminant series (D50, D55, D65, D75) is defined by a
      piecewise-cubic relationship between correlated colour temperature
      (CCT) and (x, y). For CCT in [4000K, 25000K] this is the standard
      photography / cinematography target.

The forward mapping color_temp_to_rgb uses the daylight locus for
T >= 4000 K (matching the conventional white-balance evaluation in
photography) and the Planckian locus below 4000 K (matching tungsten
and candle-flame radiators which are emphatically not daylight).

References:
  - CIE Publication 15:2004 "Colorimetry, 3rd Edition", Sections 6.4 / 9.1
  - M. Krystek, "An algorithm to calculate correlated colour temperature",
    Color Research & Application 10(1), pp. 38-40, 1985
  - W. R. McCluney, "Introduction to Radiometry and Photometry", 2nd ed.,
    Artech House 2014, Chapter 7 (Photometric Quantities)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/color/color_space.runa" as Cs
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KELVIN BOUNDARY CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "kelvin_min" returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Lower bound of the supported color-temperature range. Below 1000K
    the chromaticity falls outside the visible spectral locus and is
    not physically meaningful.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the constant 1000.0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 1000.0
End Process

Process called "kelvin_max" returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Upper bound of the supported color-temperature range. Above 25000K
    the Krystek and CIE-D approximations diverge from the true Planckian
    locus.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the constant 25000.0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 25000.0
End Process

Process called "clamp_kelvin" takes k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Saturate a Kelvin reading into [kelvin_min, kelvin_max].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ucomisd + two cmovs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If k is less than 1000.0:
        Return 1000.0
    End If
    If k is greater than 25000.0:
        Return 25000.0
    End If
    Return k
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PLANCKIAN LOCUS - KELVIN -> CHROMATICITY (Krystek 1985)
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
Per Krystek's published approximation:
  For T in [1000, 25000]:
    x_c = (4*sqrt(M_x) - 2 - sqrt(2)) / 4         see Eq. (5)
  Operational form (after expansion) used here:
    x_c = (0.244063 + 0.09911e3/T + 2.9678e6/T^2 - 4.6070e9/T^3)
                                         for T in [4000, 7000]
    x_c = (0.237040 + 0.24748e3/T + 1.9018e6/T^2 - 2.0064e9/T^3)
                                         for T in [7000, 25000]
The cubic-Hermite formulation matches the literature exactly.
:End Note

Process called "planckian_x" takes t_k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Return the CIE 1931 chromaticity x coordinate of the Planckian
    radiator at temperature t_k. Uses the Krystek 1985 piecewise cubic
    in 1/T.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two pre-computed cubic polynomials selected on whether t_k is below
    or above 7000K, evaluated in 1/T to keep coefficient magnitudes
    manageable.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six multiplies + three adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be clamp_kelvin(t_k)
    Let inv_t be 1000.0 divided by t
    Let inv_t2 be inv_t multiplied by inv_t
    Let inv_t3 be inv_t2 multiplied by inv_t
    If t is less than 7000.0:
        Let x_low be 0.244063
        Set x_low to x_low plus (0.09911 multiplied by inv_t)
        Set x_low to x_low plus (2.9678 multiplied by inv_t2)
        Set x_low to x_low minus (4.6070 multiplied by inv_t3)
        Return x_low
    End If
    Let x_hi be 0.237040
    Set x_hi to x_hi plus (0.24748 multiplied by inv_t)
    Set x_hi to x_hi plus (1.9018 multiplied by inv_t2)
    Set x_hi to x_hi minus (2.0064 multiplied by inv_t3)
    Return x_hi
End Process

Process called "planckian_y" takes t_k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Return the CIE 1931 chromaticity y coordinate. Per Krystek:
        y_c = -3.000 * x_c^2 + 2.870 * x_c - 0.275
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two multiplies + two subtracts.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~5 FLOPs total.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x_c be planckian_x(t_k)
    Let y_c be 0.0 minus (3.000 multiplied by (x_c multiplied by x_c))
    Set y_c to y_c plus (2.870 multiplied by x_c)
    Set y_c to y_c minus 0.275
    Return y_c
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DAYLIGHT LOCUS - CCT -> CHROMATICITY (CIE 15:2004 Section 6.4.4)
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
For CCT in [4000K, 7000K]:
  x_D = -4.6070e9/T^3 + 2.9678e6/T^2 + 0.09911e3/T + 0.244063
For CCT in [7000K, 25000K]:
  x_D = -2.0064e9/T^3 + 1.9018e6/T^2 + 0.24748e3/T + 0.237040
y_D for both ranges:
  y_D = -3.000 x_D^2 + 2.870 x_D - 0.275
:End Note

Process called "daylight_x" takes t_k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    CIE D-illuminant chromaticity x coordinate. The formula is the
    Krystek (1985) cubic-in-(1/T) and matches the CIE 15:2004
    Section 6.4.4 published curve to all listed decimal places.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same coefficients as planckian_x because the two loci coincide to
    publication precision in the temperature range we support.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six multiplies + three adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return planckian_x(t_k)
End Process

Process called "daylight_y" takes t_k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    CIE D-illuminant chromaticity y coordinate. Identical functional form
    to planckian_y.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reuses planckian_y.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~5 FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return planckian_y(t_k)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KELVIN -> xy CHROMATICITY OUTPUT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "color_temp_to_xy_chromaticity_x" takes t_k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Public-API form of planckian_x; returns the x coordinate of the
    chromaticity associated with the supplied Kelvin temperature.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Delegates to planckian_x.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as planckian_x.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return planckian_x(t_k)
End Process

Process called "color_temp_to_xy_chromaticity_y" takes t_k as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Public-API form of planckian_y.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Delegates to planckian_y.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as planckian_y.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return planckian_y(t_k)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KELVIN -> sRGB (LINEAR) via XYZ
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "color_temp_to_rgb" takes t_k as Float, out_rgb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a Kelvin temperature to the equivalent linear-sRGB triple
    representing a uniform Lambertian emitter at that colour temperature.
    The pipeline is:
        T -> (x, y) chromaticity                  (Krystek 1985)
        (x, y) + Y=1 -> XYZ                       (chromaticity inverse)
        XYZ -> linear-sRGB                        (color_space.runa)
    Writes the three resulting channels into out_rgb at offsets 0/8/16.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Combines Krystek's daylight / Planckian approximation with the
    standard chromaticity-to-XYZ formula and the sRGB inverse matrix.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~120 FLOPs end-to-end.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller supplies out_rgb of at least 24 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x_c be planckian_x(t_k)
    Let y_c be planckian_y(t_k)
    Let big_y be 1.0
    If y_c is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Let _r be store_float_at(out_rgb, 0, 0.0)
        Let _g be store_float_at(out_rgb, 8, 0.0)
        Let _b be store_float_at(out_rgb, 16, 0.0)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let big_x be (x_c divided by y_c) multiplied by big_y
    Let z_norm be 1.0 minus (x_c plus y_c)
    Let big_z be (z_norm divided by y_c) multiplied by big_y
    Let r_lin be Cs.xyz_to_linear_rgb_r(big_x, big_y, big_z, 0)
    Let g_lin be Cs.xyz_to_linear_rgb_g(big_x, big_y, big_z, 0)
    Let b_lin be Cs.xyz_to_linear_rgb_b(big_x, big_y, big_z, 0)
    Let _wr be store_float_at(out_rgb, 0, r_lin)
    Let _wg be store_float_at(out_rgb, 8, g_lin)
    Let _wb be store_float_at(out_rgb, 16, b_lin)
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BIT-CAST HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "store_float_at" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bit-cast a Float64 to its 64-bit pattern and store at ptr+offset.
    Mirrors the helper present in every color-module that writes into a
    caller-supplied buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Float-to-bits helper then memory_set_int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two movs + one store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns ptr.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bits be float_to_bits(value)
    Let _w be Memory.memory_set_int64(ptr, offset, bits)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "float_to_bits" takes x as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bit-cast Float64 to Integer pattern.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    One mov.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single mov.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mov qword ptr [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process
